The 2009 Indian general elections were held in five phases from April 16 to May 13, 2009. The main contenders were the Indian National Congress (INC), led by Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, and the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), led by L.K. Advani. The INC emerged as the single largest party, winning 206 out of 543 seats in the Lok Sabha (the lower house of India's Parliament). The INC-led United Progressive Alliance (UPA) coalition secured a total of 262 seats, enabling Manmohan Singh to continue as Prime Minister for a second consecutive term. The BJP and its allies, forming the National Democratic Alliance (NDA), won 159 seats. The elections saw a significant victory for the INC, indicating public satisfaction with the UPA government's performance and policies
